<section xml:id="section-activity-clo16">
  <title>Activity for CLO-16</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo16-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is sigma notation?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Sigma notation is notation using the upper case sigma,
          <m>\Sigma</m>, to write long sums. It's a common notation in
          many parts of mathematics, since many ideas and
          constructions rely on the ability to write arbitrary large
          sums in a concise way. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How can area under a curve be approximated by rectangles?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The area can be approximated by dividing the domain into
          smaller piece. Then, over each piece, a rectangle can be
          drawn with height roughly matching the curve. The sum of the
          areas of these rectangles is an approximation to the area
          under the curve. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the Riemann integral?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p> 
        The Riemann integral is the limit of the process of using
        rectangle to approximation areas under curves. As the number
        of rectangles increases, the approximation gets more and more
        accurate. In the limit at the numbers of rectangles increases
        without bound, the approximation approaches a fixed value,
        which is exactly the area under the curve. The result is the
        Riemann definition of the integral. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is an integrable function?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An integrable function is a function for which the Riemann
          integral limit converges, hence the area under the graph of
          the function can be determined by integration. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the bound of an integral?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The bounds of an integral are the end points of the interval
          over which the integral is defined. In the notation, they
          are placed at the bottom and top of the integral symbol. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-sigma-notation">
    <title>Calcluation Questions: Sigma Notation</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in ordinary notation. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=2}^9 i^2 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Starting at 2, I replace <m>i</m> with all the numbers up
          to 9 and then add all these results together.
          <md>
            <mrow>
             \amp \sum_{i=2}^9 i^2 = 2^2 + 3^2 + 4^2 + 5^2 + 6^2 + 7^2
             + 8^2 + 9^2 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 + 9 + 16 + 25 + 36 + 49 + 64 + 81
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in ordinary notation. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=-3}^{10} (6i-4)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Starting at <m>-3</m>, I replace <m>i</m> with all the
          numbers up to 10 and then add all these results together. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \sum_{i=-3}^{10} (6i-4) = (6(-3) - 4) +  (6(-2) -
              4) + (6(-1) - 4) +  (6(0) - 4)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (6(1) - 4) +  
              (6(2) - 4) +  
              (6(3) - 4) +  
              (6(4) - 4) +  
              (6(5) - 4) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (6(6) - 4) +  
              (6(7) - 4) +  
              (6(8) - 4) +  
              (6(9) - 4) +  
              (6(10) - 4) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = -22 + (-16) + (-10) + (-4) + 2 + 8 + 14 + 20 + 26
              + 32
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + 38 + 44 + 50 + 56
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in ordinary notation. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=0}^{15} 2^i
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Starting with 0, I replace <m>i</m> with all the numbers up
          to 15 and then add all the resulting numbers together. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \sum_{i=0}^{15} 2^i = 2^0 + 2^1 + 2^2 + 2^3 + 2^4 +
              2^5 + 2^6 + 2^7 + 2^8 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + 2^9 + 2^{10} + 2^{11} + 2^{12} + 2^{13}
              + 2^{14} + 2^{15} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 1 + 2 + 4 + 8 + 16 + 32 + 64 + 128 + 256 + 512 +
              1024
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + 2048 + 4096 + 8192 + 16384 + 32768
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in ordinary notation. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=3}^7 (i^2 + 5i - 3^i)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Starting with 3, I replace <m>i</m> will all the number
          until 7. Then I add up all the resulting numbers. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \sum_{i=3}^7 (i^2 + 5i - 3^i) = (3^2 + 5(3) - 3^3)
              + (4^2 + 5(4) - 3^4) + (5^2 + 5(5) - 3^5)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (6^2 + 5(6) -
              3^6) + (7^2 + 5(7) - 3^7) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = (9 + 15 - 27) + (16 + 20 - 81) + (25 + 25 - 243)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (36 + 30 - 729) + (49 + 35 - 2187)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = (-3) + (-45) + (-193) + (-663) + (-2103)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in sigma notation.
          <md>
            1 + 4 + 7 + 10 + 13 + 16 + 19
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need a pattern. This is an arithmetic sequence, where
          each step is adding 3. I start with a value of 1. Using this,
          I can start at <m>i=0</m> and describe this pattern as <m>1
          + 3i</m>. The value of <m>i</m> that gives 19 is <m>i=6</m>,
          so the sum will end at 6. 
          <md>
            1 + 4 + 7 + 10 + 13 + 16 + 19 = \sum_{i=0}^6 (1+3i)
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in sigma notation.
          <md>
            3 + 6 + 12 + 24 + 48 + 96
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need a pattern. This is a geometric sequence, where
          each steps multiplies by 2. I start with a value of 3. Using
          this, I can start at <m>i=0</m> and describe this pattern
          as <m>3(2^i)</m>. The value of <m>i</m> that gives 96 is
          <m>i = 5</m>, so the sum will end at 6.
          <md>
            3 + 6 + 12 + 24 + 48 + 96 = \sum_{i=0}^5 3(2^i)
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this sum in sigma notation.
          <md>
            16 + 14 + 12 + 10 + 8 + 6 + 4 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I need a pattern. I have a couple options. I could keep
          this in ths order is it written in, start from 16, and
          subtract 2 in each step. I could also change the order and
          write this as an arithmetic progression starting at 4. I'll
          chose the first option, starting with <m>i=0</m> and writing
          <m>16 -2i</m> for the pattern. When <m>i=6</m>, I get the
          last term, so the sum will end at 6. 
          <md>
            16 + 14 + 12 + 10 + 8 + 6 + 4 = \sum_{i=0}^6 (16-2i)
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use linearity to split this into several sums with constants
          removed. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=0}^{44} (5i^3 - 2i^2 - 19i + 19)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Linearity splits up the sum over addition and subtraction
          and allows me to pull out the constants. In each piece, the
          index and bounds of the sum stay the same. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=0}^{44} (5i^3 - 2i^2 - 19i + 19) = 5
            \sum_{i=0}^{44} i^3 - 2 \sum_{i=0}^{44} i^2 - 19
            \sum_{i=0}^{44} i + 19 \sum_{i=0}^{44} 1
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use linearity to split this into several sums with constants
          removed. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=4}^{104} (-12i^5 + i^3 - 71i^2 + 4)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Linearity splits up the sum over addition and subtraction
          and allows me to pull out the constants. In each piece, the
          index and bounds of the sum stay the same. 
          <md>
            \sum_{i=4}^{104} (-12i^5 + i^3 - 71i^2 + 4) = 
            -12 \sum_{i=4}^{104} i^5 + \sum_{i=4}^{104} i^3 - 71
            \sum_{i=4}^{104} i^2 + 4 \sum_{i=4}^{104} 1
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use linearity to combine this into one sum. 
          <md>
            4 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i^3 - 15 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i^2 - 7
            \sum_{i=0}^{10} i + 9 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The indices and bounds of all the sums are the same, so I
          can combine them into one sum by taking the constants inside
          the sums and writing the additions and subtractions inside
          the sum. Notice there are two <m>i</m> terms, which I can
          combine into one. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              4 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i^3 - 15 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i^2 - 7
              \sum_{i=0}^{10} i + 9 \sum_{i=0}^{10} i \amp =
              \sum_{i=0}^{10} (4i^3 - 15i^2 - 7i + 9i) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \sum_{i=0}^{10} (4i^3 - 15i^2 + 2i)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use linearity to combine this into one sum. 
          <md>
            19 \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^3 - \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^3 + 2
            \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^2 - 36 \sum_{i=4}^{17} i 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The indices and bounds of all the sums are the same, so I
          can combine them into one sum by taking the constants inside
          the sums and writing the additions and subtractions inside
          the sum. Notice there are two <m>i^3</m> terms, which I can
          combine into one. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              19 \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^3 - \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^3 + 2
              \sum_{i=4}^{17} i^2 - 36 \sum_{i=4}^{17} i \amp = 
              \sum_{i=4}^{17} (19i^3 - i^3 + 2i^2 - 36 i) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \sum_{i=4}^{17} (18i^3 + 2i^2 - 36 i)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-riemann-integral">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Riemann Integral</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          This is a multi-part activity to solve the integral 
          <md>
            \int_{-1}^1 (x^2 + 2x + 2)dx
          </md>
          by definition using the Reimann definition of the integral.
          First, write the definition of the integral and replace the
          general pieces with the specifics of this function.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Here is the general form.
          <md>
            \int_a^b f(x) dx = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}
            \sum_{k=1}^n f(x_k^*) \left( \frac{b-a}{n} \right) 
          </md>
          In this situation, <m>a = -1</m>, <m>b = 1</m> and <m>f(x) =
          (x^2 + 2x +2)</m>. I put these into the general form. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_{-1}^1 (x^2 + 2x + 2) dx \amp = \lim_{n
              \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \left( (x_k^*)^2 +
              2x_k^* + 2 \right) \left( \frac{1-(-1)}{n} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \left(
              (x_k^*)^2 + 2x_k^* + 2 \right) \left( \frac{2}{n}
              \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          When write an expression for <m>x_k^*</m> and use it in the
          expression.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There is a general form for <m>x_k^*</m> that I have been
          using in the examples. 
          <md>
            x_k^* = a + k \frac{b-a}{n} 
          </md>
          Now I put in the values for this particular integral.
          <md>
            x_k^* = -1 + k \frac{1-(-1)}{n}  = -1 + \frac{2k}{n} 
          </md>
          Then I can return to the form from the previous section and
          replace <m>x_k^*</m> with this new expression. I'll proceed
          to simplify the polynomial after I've substituted <m>x_k^*</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_{-1}^1 (x^2+2+2) dx \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}
              \sum_{k=1}^n \left( \left( -1 + \frac{2k}{n} \right)^2 +
              2 \left( -1 + \frac{2k}{n} \right) + 2 \right) \left(
              \frac{2}{n} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \left(
              1 - \frac{4k}{n} + \frac{4k^2}{n^2} + -2  - \frac{4k}{n}
              + 2 \right) \left( \frac{2}{n} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \left(
              1 + \frac{4k^2}{n^2} \right) \left( \frac{2}{n} \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \sum_{k=1}^n \left(
              \frac{2}{n} + \frac{8k^2}{n^3} \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Then rearrange and split up the sum using linearity. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are two pieces of this sum from the end of the previous
          part. I split this into two sums and pull out the
          constants. Note that <m>k</m> is the index of the sum, so
          anything that doesn't involve <m>k</m> is a constant. That
          means that <m>n</m> is a constant as far as the sum is
          concerned and can be brought outside.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_{-1}^1 (x^2+2x+2) dx \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty}
              \sum_{k=1}^n \left( \frac{2}{n} + \frac{8k^2}{n^3}
              \right) 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( \sum_{k=1}^n
              \frac{2}{n} + \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{8k^2}{n^3} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( \frac{2}{n}
              \sum_{k=1}^n 1+ \frac{8}{n^3} \sum_{k=1}^n k^2 \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Then replace the remaining sums with their values according
          to the standard sum formulas. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          From the previous step, there are sums with terms 1 and
          <m>k^2</m>. These are standard sums which can be evaluated.
          After the replacement, I can simplify the expression a
          bit.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( \frac{2}{n}
              \sum_{k=1}^n 1 + \frac{8}{n^3} \sum_{k=1}^n k^2 \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( \frac{2}{n} n + 
              \frac{8}{n^3} \frac{n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( 2 +
              \frac{8n(n+1)(2n+1)}{6n^3} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( 2 + \frac{8n(2n^2 +
              3n + 1)}{6n^3} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( 2 + \frac{16n^3 +
              24n^2 + 8n)}{6n^3} \right)
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Finally, use asymptotic analysis to solve the limit. Write
          the final value of the integral. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The constant term 2 remains unchanged in the limit. The other
          term is a fraction with <m>n^3</m> in the numerator and
          denominator. Since these have the same asymptotic order,
          asymptotic analysis tells that the limit is the ratio of the
          leading coefficients. 
          <md>
            \lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} \left( 2 + \frac{16n^3 +
            24n^2 + 8n)}{6n^3} \right) = 2 + \frac{16}{6} = 2 +
            \frac{8}{3} = \frac{14}{3}
          </md>
          This completes the integral. The area under the curve
          described by the original problem is <m>\frac{14}{3}</m>
          units squared. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
